    std::string html = "<!DOCTYPE html><html><head><title>Your Markdown Title</title>";
    html += "<body><p>" + markdown + "</p>";
    html += "<h1>Heading 1</h1><h2>Heading 2</h2>";
    html += "<ul><li>Item 1</li><li>Item 2</li></ul>";
    html += "<pre><code>markdown code here</code></pre>";
    html += "</body></html>";
    html += "</head></body>";
    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "This is a *emphasized* sentence";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This function takes a reference to the `markdown` `std::string` and initializes an empty `std::string` called `html`. It then begins building the HTML document by adding the `<!DOCTYPE html>` and `<html>` tags, followed by the `<head>` and `<body>` tags. The `<body>` tag is where the Markdown text is placed, surrounded by `<p>` tags. Heading elements like `<h1>` and `<h2>` are also added, as well as an `<ul>` element with `<li>` items. Finally, a `<pre>` element with a code block is added.

The function then returns the completed `html` string. In the `main` function, we demonstrate the function by passing the Markdown text "This is a *emphasized* sentence" as input and displaying the resulting HTML output.

